{meta: title I Hear the South Calling Me}
{meta: artist Hank Thompson}
{meta: writer R.C. Bannon and John Bettis}

{start_of_verse: Verse 1}
[G]I hear the south calling me
[C]I've been away much to [G]long
[C]Mason Dixon fevers won't leave me [G]alone
[A7]The only cure I know for sure is a one way ticket [D7]home
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 2}
[G]Watermelons ripe on the vine
[C]Catfish a nibbling on my [G]line
[C]Slow southern draws
[G]And home made [A7]alcohol
[D7]I hear the south calling [G]me
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 3}
I hear the south calling me
[C]I've been away much to [G]long
[C]Big city blues sure got my [G]soul
[A7]Keep it country bars and steel guitars
[D7]And a Dixie rock and roll
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 4}
[G]I've had those New York satins on
[C]I've had my feel of it [G]all
[C]This time I fell for some sweet southern [G]bell
[D7]I hear the south calling [G]me
[D7]I hear the south calling [G]me
{end_of_verse}
